  <!-- Delete button -->
  <button class="delete-button" id="delete-button">Delete</button>
  <!-- Other buttons -->
  <button class="other-button">Other Button</button>
</div>
```

### CSS

```css
/* Hide the delete button for non-admin users */
.delete-button {
  display: none;
}

/* Show the delete button for admin users */
.delete-button.show {
  display: block;
}
```

### JavaScript

```javascript
// Get the delete button
const deleteButton = document.getElementById('delete-button');

// Function to check if the user is an admin
function isAdmin(user) {
  // Replace this with your actual admin check logic
  return user.isAdmin;
}

// Function to toggle the delete button
function toggleDeleteButton() {
  if (isAdmin(user)) {
    deleteButton.classList.add('show');
  } else {
    deleteButton.classList.remove('show');
  }
}

// Call the toggle function when the page loads
toggleDeleteButton();
```

### Example Use Case

In your application, you can call the `isAdmin` function to check if the current user is an admin. If the user is an admin, you can call the `toggleDeleteButton` function to show the delete button. If the user is not an admin, you can call the `toggleDeleteButton` function to hide the delete button.

### Security Considerations

When checking if a user is an admin, make sure to use a secure method to verify their role. You can use a token-based system, where the user's role is stored in a token that is verified on each request.

### Best Practices

* Always validate user input to prevent security vulnerabilities.
* Use a secure method to store and verify user credentials.
* Use a secure method to check if a user is an admin.
* Use a secure method to toggle the delete button.

By following these steps and best practices, you can ensure that the delete button is only visible to admin users and is secure.

